%20The%20first%20month%20was%20tiresome%20and%20stressful%2C%20and%20I%20realized%20I%20wouldn't%20last%20another%2040%20years%20on%20Wall%20Street.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EI%20was%20making%20%2440%2C000%20a%20year%20in%20twice-monthly%20payments.%20If%20I%20invested%2050%25%20of%20my%20income%20for%2020%20years%2C%20I%20would%20save%20at%20least%2020%20years%20of%20living%20expenses.%20I%20could%20work%20until%2042%2C%20then%20live%20on%205%20to%208%25%20of%20my%20savings%2C%20stocks%2C%20and%20potential%20real%20estate%20income%20each%20year%20to%20get%20to%2062.%20I'd%20be%20set%20for%20life.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%227a9bf5fb-6774-4e38-b440-d824330d1515%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EIt%20was%20easy%20to%20save%20money%20because%20I%20was%20working%20so%20much%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EI%20started%20saving%20only%20a%20month%20after%20starting%20at%20Goldman%20Sachs.%20Every%20month%2C%20I%20invested%20half%20my%20paycheck%20into%20the%20S%26amp%3BP%20500%2C%20a%20smattering%20of%20random%20tech%20stock%2C%20and%205%25%20of%20that%20half%20into%20a%20general%20savings%20account.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAfter%20being%20advised%20by%20someone%20in%20our%20HR%20department%2C%20I%20maxed%20out%20my%20401(k).%20The%20fewer%20taxes%20I%20had%20to%20pay%2C%20the%20better%20for%20my%20savings%20goals%2C%20and%20there%20was%20a%20401(k)%20match%20at%20my%20company.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EI%20was%20able%20to%20save%20so%20much%20because%20I%20was%20very%20frugal.%20For%20the%20first%20two%20years%20at%20Goldman%20Sachs%2C%20I%20lived%20in%20a%20studio%20apartment%20in%20Manhattan%2C%20paying%20%24700%20monthly%20rent.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOne%20of%20the%20perks%20of%20working%20past%207%20p.m.%20was%20that%20you%20could%20go%20into%20the%20free%20cafeteria.%20I%20would%20eat%20dinner%20there%20and%20bring%20home%20leftovers%20for%20the%20next%20day.%20I%20also%20stuck%20to%20a%20spending%20budget%20for%20myself.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIt%20was%20a%20plan%20born%20out%20of%20misery.%20I%20was%20working%2060-plus%20hours%20a%20week%2C%20every%20week.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%226244763e-a43e-47c9-a74e-7d9299b031ec%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EA%20promotion%20and%20move%20to%20San%20Francisco%20got%20me%20on%20the%20property%20ladder%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20June%202001%2C%20I%20was%20recruited%20to%20join%20Credit%20Suisse%20and%20moved%20to%20San%20Francisco.%20My%20base%20salary%20jumped%20to%20%2485%2C000.%20Now%20I%20was%20making%20more%2C%20I%20saved%2060%25%20of%20each%20paycheck%2C%20putting%20money%20into%20long-term%20CDs%2C%20which%20are%20savings%20accounts%20with%20a%20high%20fixed%20interest%20rate%20that%20you%20can't%20withdraw%20money%20for%20a%20fixed%20period.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%202003%2C%20at%20age%2026%2C%20I%20decided%20to%20buy%20a%20two-bedroom%20apartment%20in%20San%20Francisco%20using%20the%20money%20I%20had%20earned%20and%20saved%20from%201999%20to%202003.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMy%20goal%20was%20to%20diversify%20my%20wealth%20away%20from%20equities%20into%20real%20estate.%20I%20used%2080%25%20of%20my%20savings%20and%20liquid%20investments%20to%20put%20a%2025%25%20down%20payment%20on%20a%20condo.%20I%20lived%20there%20with%20my%20then-girlfriend%2C%20who%20helped%20pay%20for%20some%20expenses.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBy%2027%2C%20I%20was%20promoted%20to%20vice%20president%20at%20Credit%20Suisse%2C%20and%20my%20income%20jumped%20to%20six%20figures%20plus%20larger%20potential%20bonuses.%20I%20saved%20and%20invested%20around%2070%25%20of%20my%20after-tax%20income%20in%202003%2C%202004%2C%20and%202005.%20In%202005%2C%20I%20bought%20a%20house%20for%20%241%2C520%2C000%20in%20San%20Francisco%20and%20rented%20my%20condo%20until%20I%20sold%20it%20in%202017.%20I%20had%20used%20up%20all%20my%20savings%20and%20investments%20to%20buy%20the%20house.%20It%20was%20a%20huge%20risk.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22189eb182-a293-4075-bd14-fa63c03dbb08%5C%22%3E%3Cstrong%3EThe%202009%20crash%20slashed%20my%20net%20worth%20but%20launched%20my%20blogging%20career%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EI%20continued%20my%20saving%20plan%20until%20the%20housing%20and%20stock%20markets%20crashed%20in%202009.%20I%20didn't%20get%20laid%20off%20in%20the%20crash%2C%20but%20I%20did%20lose%20between%2035%20and%2040%25%20of%20my%20net%20worth%20in%20six%20months%20when%20stocks%20and%20real%20estate%20prices%20cratered.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EI%20started%20my%20blog%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.financialsamurai.com%2Franking-the-best-passive-income-investments%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EFinancial%20Samurai%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20in%202009%20to%20heal.%20The%20more%20I%20wrote%2C%20the%20better%20I%20felt%20because%20I%20had%20connected%20with%20other%20people%20going%20through%20the%20same%20fears%20on%20the%20road%20to%20financial%20independence.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20October%202011%2C%20at%2034%2C%20I%20was%20making%20a%20%24250%2C000%20base%20salary.%20Credit%20Suisse%20had%20undergone%20several%20layoffs%20during%20the%20global%20financial%20crisis.%20I%20spoke%20with%20my%20HR%20manager%2C%20who%20said%20more%20layoffs%20were%20coming.%20This%20was%20my%20exit%20to%20early%20retirement.%20I%20talked%20to%20my%20manager%20and%20asked%20him%20to%20consider%20laying%20me%20off%20with%20a%20severance%20package%20and%20deferred%20compensation%20if%20I%20stayed%20on%20to%20train%20my%20junior%20employee.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBy%20April%202012%2C%20I%20was%20laid%20off%20and%20received%20the%20severance%20package%20I'd%20negotiated.%20It%20felt%20scary%2C%20but%20also%20like%20I%20had%20won%20the%20lottery.%20The%20severance%20covered%20multiple%20years%20of%20my%20projected%20living%20expenses.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%228ef34fee-a28f-4df7-8f42-b66f0aaf2f56%5C%22%3ERetiring%20at%2034%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EI%20retired%20at%2034%20with%20a%20net%20worth%20was%20around%20%242.5%20million%20after%20saving%20and%20investing%2050%20to%2075%25%20of%20my%20income%20for%2012%20years.%20I%20made%20around%20%2480%2C000%20of%20passive%20income%20from%20rent%2C%20stock%20dividends%2C%20and%20CD%20income%20a%20year.%20I%20continued%20to%20save%2050%25%20of%20my%20income%20and%20live%20on%20%2440%2C000.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20my%20final%20year%20at%20work%2C%20I'd%20been%20saving%20even%20more%20of%20my%20income%2C%20around%2080%25%2C%20so%20the%20adjustment%20to%20living%20off%20less%20wasn't%20huge.%20It%20was%20outweighed%20by%20the%20increased%20freedom%20I%20had.%20After%20I%20retired%2C%20I%20realized%20I%20didn't%20need%20as%20much%20money%20as%20I'd%20thought%20to%20be%20happy.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%202015%2C%20my%20wife%20also%20retired.%20She's%20three%20years%20younger%20than%20me%2C%20and%20we%20planned%20for%20her%20to%20retire%20by%2035.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOnce%20she%20left%2C%20we%20had%20to%20pay%20for%20full%20healthcare%20benefits.%20It%20cost%20us%20around%20%241%2C680%20monthly%20in%20healthcare%20premiums%20because%20we%20didn't%20qualify%20for%20subsidies.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%223ca38440-16fc-41ba-8d54-124681bb2f33%5C%22%3EHaving%20kids%20took%20up%20a%20lot%20of%20our%20passive%20income%20budget%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EOnce%20our%20son%20was%20born%20in%202017%2C%20we%20began%20spending%20more%20of%20our%20passive%20income.%20We%20spent%20even%20more%20of%20our%20passive%20income%20when%20our%20daughter%20was%20born%20in%202019.%20We%20now%20pay%20%242%2C500%20monthly%20for%20unsubsidized%20healthcare%20premiums%20for%20a%20family%20of%20four.%20Preschool%20for%20each%20child%20was%20as%20much%20as%20%243%2C200%20a%20month.%20We%20are%20spending%20nearly%20100%25%20of%20our%20passive%20income%20now.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EI%20believe%20I've%20failed%20early%20retirement.%20Despite%20lasting%2012%20years%20without%20a%20job%2C%20I%20recognize%20I%20need%20to%20save%20and%20earn%20more%20to%20generate%20more%20passive%20income.%20I%20didn't%20anticipate%20having%20two%20kids%20after%20trying%20so%20long%20for%20one.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhen%20we%20retired%2C%20my%20wife%20and%20I%20were%20lo